### Footnotes

<span id="fn_217"></span>[51:1](sbe30017.htm#fr_217.md) 5, 1. The
*K*aturthîkarman.

<span id="fn_218"></span>[51:2](sbe30017.htm#fr_218.md) 2, 3. Comp.
*S*âṅkhâyana-G*ri*hya I, 18, 3; Khâdira-G*ri*hya I, 4, 12.

<span id="fn_219"></span>[51:4](sbe30017.htm#fr_219.md) I.e. instead of
prâya*sk*itte (expiation) he uses the plural prâya*sk*ittaya*h*; and he
says, 'you are the expiations of the gods,' &c.

<span id="fn_220"></span>[51:6](sbe30017.htm#fr_220.md) Khâdira-G*ri*hya I,
4,13. Hrâsayitvâ literally means, 'having shortened her.' She is
'shortened' by the removing of the substance with which they have
besmeared her (hrâsayitvâ udvartanâdinâ tad abhya*ñg*anam apanîya, says
the commentary). Comp. on the technical meaning of hrâsana the
G*ri*hya-sa*m*graha II, 38, 8-10; Khâdira-G*ri*hya I, 4, 15. 16.

